Nairobi National Park, Kenya -- tPart 3. Circulation of Environmental Knowledge: Networks, Expertise, and Science in Practice -- tIntroduction -- t11. Rooted Networks, Webs of Relation, and the Power of Situated Science: Bringing the Models Back Down to Earth in Zambrana -- t12. Circulating Science, Incompletely Regulating Commodities: Governing from a Distance in Transnational Agro- Food Networks -- t13. Reclaiming the Technological Imagination: Water, Power, and Place in India -- t14. Circulating Knowledge, Constructing Expertise -- t15. Experiments as “Performances”: Interpreting Farmers’ Soil Fertility Management Practices in Western Kenya -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolitical ecology and science studies have found fertile meeting ground in environmental studies. While the two distinct areas of inquiry approach the environment from different perspectives—one focusing on the politics of resource access and the other on the construction and perception of knowledge—their work is actually more closely aligned now than ever before. Knowing Nature brings together political ecologists and science studies scholars to showcase the key points of encounter between the two fields and how this intellectual mingling creates a lively and more robust ecological framework for the study of environmental politics. The contributors all actively work at the interface between these two fields, and here they use empirical material to explore questions of theoretical and practical import for understanding the politics that surround nature-society relations, from wildlife management in the Yukon to soil fertility in Kenya. In addition, they examine how various environmental knowledge claims are generated, packaged, promoted, and accepted (or rejected) by the different actors involved in specific cases of environmental management, conservation, and development. Finally, they ask what is at stake in the struggles surrounding environmental knowledge, how such struggles shape conceptions of the environment, and whose interests are served in the process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnvironmental sciences. 0aPolitical ecology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascience, scientific, scientist, ecological, politics, intersection, interdisciplinary, environmental, environment, college, university, higher education, classroom, textbook, professor, resource, access, knowledge, intellectual, framework, academic, scholarly, theoretical, nature, wildlife, management, practical, society, research, natural world, essay collection, sociology, species, colonial, national park, international.1 aCampbell, Lisa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvall, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsyth, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujimura, Joan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalt, Ryan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Mara J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Mara J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIngram, Mrill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLave, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee Peluso, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadasdy, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadasdy, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhadke, Roopali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 